# Coding Challenge Scaffolding Rule

Apply this rule **only** when the user explicitly asks to scaffold or set up a coding challenge/problem and provides a URL (not limited to LeetCode).

- Do not solve unless explicitly asked to solve.
- Always mirror existing repo conventions and naming patterns.
- Keep scaffolds deterministic, minimal, and ready for implementation.

## Required Output Structure

For a problem slug `<slug>`, create/update all of:

- `content/problems/<slug>.md`
- `solutions/<slug>/metadata.json`
- `solutions/<slug>/solution.ts`
- `solutions/<slug>/solution.test.ts`

## Scaffold Expectations

- In `content/problems/<slug>.md`:
  - frontmatter (`title`, `slug`, `source`, `difficulty`, `datePublished`, `timeComplexity`, `spaceComplexity`, `excerpt`)
  - problem statement, constraints, examples, edge-case checklist, test coverage plan
  - implementation section as a stub only (TODO / not implemented)
- In `metadata.json`:
  - same canonical metadata fields used by existing `solutions/*/metadata.json`
- In `solution.ts`:
  - exported function signature only, with TODO + defensive placeholder (no algorithm)
- In `solution.test.ts`:
  - scaffolded `bun:test` suite with real assertions and expected outputs (no `test.todo(...)`)
  - include baseline examples, happy-path coverage, edge cases, and deterministic larger-case checks
  - include at least one defensive contract test (for example, input non-mutation when relevant)

## Review Checklist Before Finalizing

- Slug is consistent across `content/problems` and `solutions`.
- Function name and export match test imports.
- No accidental solution logic included.
- Test file is comprehensive enough to guide implementation and catch regressions.
- Lints pass for created/edited files.
